iIn English class, our foreign teacher introduced us to the card game		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iRummy. This game has no official rules, so there are many variations		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iamong players.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe rules our teacher taught us are as follows:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe game requires at least one deck of playing cards, depending on the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inumber of players, with all jokers removed.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAt the start, each player is dealt 7 cards. After dealing, flip the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
itop card from the deck and place it aside.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iDuring each player's turn, they must perform the following actions:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Choose to take the top card from the face-down deck or take any		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
inumber of cards from the face-up discard pile.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen taking cards from the discard pile, you must use the bottommost		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icard you picked up during this turn according to condition 2 below.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i(Cannot keep it in hand or discard it)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- When the cards in your hand meet the following conditions, you can		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplace them on your table:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2.1. At least 3 cards of the same suit forming a sequence, e.g., ♣A23,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i♠10JQ, ♥QKA. (KA2 doesn't count)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2.2. 3 or 4 cards with the same rank but different suits.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor example, ♠3, ♥3, ♣3 is valid, but ♠3, ♠3, ♥3 is invalid. The		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilatter case can only occur when using multiple decks.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i2.3. Having a card that can extend sequences or same-rank groups as		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idescribed in 2.1 and 2.2.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- When you play a card that makes a sequence or same-rank group		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iimpossible to extend further, all players turn face-down (Closed) the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icards on their table belonging to that sequence or group.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor example, when using one deck, if there's a sequence ♣A2345 and a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isame-rank group ♠6, ♥6, ♣6 on the table. The sequence cannot be		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iextended in either direction and should be closed. If a player later		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplays ♦6, that same-rank group should also be closed.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Discard one card from your hand by placing it on top of the discard		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipile. Ensure all cards in the discard pile remain visible to all		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplayers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- All players may now check your discarded card. If it can extend		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isequences or same-rank groups as described in 2.1 and 2.2, other		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplayers can call "Rummy" to claim the card and play it immediately.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- The game ends when a player discards their last card, or when the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idraw pile is exhausted and no player can use cards from the discard		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ipile according to the rules.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Scoring: Each card on the table: 2-9 = 5 points, 10-K = 10 points, A		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i= 15 points.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iEach card remaining in hand: 2-9 = -5 points, 10-K = -10 points, A =		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i-15 points.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iA not so obvious dividing line		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn actual gameplay, with many players, it's impossible to ensure		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ieveryone sees the discard pile and cards on the table, leading to		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifrequent "Rummy" situations. I've been caught several times. Thus, I		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icreated a card counting program to track the game state.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSince it needs to work on both computers and phones, this program is		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iweb-based using Javascript. There are two versions.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first version is for single-deck games, offering card tracking,		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iseparate display of sequences/same-rank groups, and Rummy alerts.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
